review_blob: Had on tap at 99 bottles, santa cruz. Pours golden with thin head. Aroma is sweet and malty. Flavor is way too sweet and tons of alcohol. Pretty much just awful. Only drank half my glass.
This is what the younger crowd in CR drinks when they are trying to get fd up. Basically higher alcohol fizzy yellow beer. It tastes exactly how you would imagine....
When your in CR this is the beer you choose when youre going for maximum buzz, its got a little more kick than the imperial. Other than that... it basically tastes like a bad malt liquor.
Another fizzy light beer in a beautiful country. Tastes good while sitting on the beach, watching the sun set, and smoking a (real) cohiba.
Pretty standard fizzy, light, lager. The best part about this beer is the location you should be drinking it: on a beach in CR.

Probably the most flavorful local brew you can get in CR. The problem is when youre in CR you want a beer that is light and refreshing! Nonetheless, this beer has good malt (caramel), light sweetness, and is smooth. Not bad for a mass-produced 3rd-world brew!
Nice stout here. Lots of roasted flavors but not too much of the burnt. Light sweetness. Very smooth. Nice.
beer_name: Buffalo Bills Johnny Midnite Oatmeal Stout

review_blob: Solid IPA here. Plenty of good citrus and pine but well-balanced by nice sweet caramel malt. Well done.
Malty beer with some alcohol coming through. Not much sweetness or bitterness. Lacks balance.
Strong malty aroma and flavor are what define this brew. Good notes of carmel and a nice sweetness. Not bad.
Pretty standard brewpub hefe here. Cloudy yellow with thin head. Grainy with some notes of clove. Thin and refreshing.
Very standard pale lager here. Nothing stands out about this brew. But, theres no flaws with it either.

Pours deep amber brown with a thin but lasting head. Aroma is big and reeks of juicy citrus and sweet malt. Flavor is just as bold and nicely balanced. Full bodied and sweet fades into a nice smooth bitterness. Another round please!

I bought this beer for the massive .52gal bottle that it comes in, basically works as a nice big growler. Didnt have enough shelf room in the fridge to store this bottle upright so had to keep it on its side... Pours golden with tons of precipitates floating around. This isnt your usual sediment that slowly sinks to the bottom, no this stuff isnt going anywhere. Nice sweet malty aroma. A bit of alcohol comes through in the flavor, not bad but I imagine it will begin to get harsh as the bottom of this bottle approaches.
Pours hazy amber with thick white head. Spicy, pefumey aroma. Rich yeasty flavors with malt to back it up. Not too sweet, not too dry nice.
Pours a truly opaque black. Light brown head. Aroma is all belgian. Flavor starts off belgian but then transitions to roasty/toasty/burnt flavors. Lovely complexity, nicely balanced.

This one has been sitting in the back of the fridge for way too long, time to bust this baby out. Pours hazy amber with a thin head. Nice steady stream of fine carbonation bubbles rises to the surface. Nice bold aroma of sweet malt and yeast. Flavor is very sweet, full bodied, with a smooth but strong bitter kick. Nicely balanced.

Pours clear deep amber with a thin head. Aroma is mostly carmel malt. I detect just a hint of smoke. Flavor is where the smoke really comes through. Not overpowering but definitely present. The beer is still very drinkable and quite refreshing. Nice!
Similar to the apple cider but this time with a light pear aroma to it. Pretty good.
On tap at ciderpub. Similar to their apple cider except that some notes of honey come through. I like this as it adds an additional layer of complexity.
Smells of apples and has a tart finish. Some residual sweetness. Lightly carbonated. A good apple cider.
On tap at ciderpub. Very thin, very dry, quite carbonated. Pretty much like drinking a champagne.

On tap at Firehouse. Pours deep amber/brown with a thin head. Bold, citrusy, hoppy aroma... Im excited already. Flavor: the sharpness of the rye complements the potent bitterness beautifully. Good hoppy flavor kicks the mouth and lingers for awhile. Beautifully crafted.

Good beer but not really an IPA. There is so much malt that I would classify this more as an Amber? Either way its good. Bold Centennial hop aroma is citrusy and a bit spicy. Plenty of caramel in there to balance the malt. Very flavorful and aromatic brew here. Quite complex, theres a lot going on. Medium bodied with lingering bitter finish.
Pours brown with big tan head. Aroma sweet and spicy (cloves and molasses). Flavor is more sweet, more spicy, and has an alcoholic kick. Mouthfeel is nice and round. Its good but its not great.
Pours dark brown, good lasting head. Spicy weizen aroma. Has a very distinct nutty, roasted flavor that melds nicely with the spicy components. Body is medium. Flavor is dry. Quite effervescent.

Pours opaque black, no light gets through this one. Brown head dissipates. Aromas of roasted malt, some burnt aromas, a little dark chocolate, and a certain sourness. In the flavor there is a lot of acidity probably from all of the black malt. Very rich with burnt malt, light charcoal flavors, and a mild sourness. I cant help but think this sourness may be due to some sort of sanitation problems.
beer_name: Santa Cruz Mountain Organic Devout Stout

review_blob: Pours a brilliant copper color with big offwhite lasting head. Aroma has a sourness to it. Theres so much head in the way theres not much to smell. Ewww. This beer is sour. Something is clearly wrong with it. Too bad.

Pours a cloudy golden with a lasting white head. Aroma is an interesting combination of belgian esters and northwest hops. Flavor would be sweet but the sweetness is overshadowed by obscene bitterness and alcohol. Bitter finish doesnt last very long. Very unique.

Pours black with a good tan head. Aroma is pretty mild but I smell some roasted malt and a light sweetness. Flavor is a nice combination of roasted malt with some dark chocolate. I dont detect much in terms of hops. The mouthfeel is outstanding. Its just creamy and velvety and rolls around your tongue.  Aftertaste is roasty and even a bit smokey. Very good.

Pours dark brown, good clarity, offwhite head. Aroma is roasted malt. Flavor is very roasted and actually a bit acrid. That might be ok in a stout but this is supposed to be a brown ale. Flavor is very dry. Finish is clean.
beer_name: Santa Cruz Mountain Organic Dread Brown Ale

review_blob: Popped the top and immediate aromas of peach hit my nose. This beer pours very light and appears very thin and watery... I had to check the bottle to make sure this wasnt a cider, because thats what it looks like. Lasting big white head and very carbonated. Not usually a big fan of fruit beers but the aroma on this is actually appealing, just peaches though, no malt no hops nothing else. Flavor is extremely dry, high level of carbonation makes it seem even drier. Not much flavor. Light bodied and refreshing. Not bad.
Pours opaque black with off-white lasting head. Roasted malt aroma. Flavor is dry with roasted malt. Body is light. Nice and easy drinking.
Aroma is fruity and yeasty but also a decent amount of hops. Flavor is similiar. Sweet medium body. Not bad.
Pours golden with thin head. Aroma is full of yeasty esters. Full bodied and sweet. Not bad.
beer_name: Marin Tripel Dipsea Belgian Style Ale

review_blob: Pop the top and we have a foamer, lost most of the neck. Good thing the beer was ice cold and I had just pulled it from the fridge. If it was warmer I probably would have lost half the bottle. A bit disappointing, thats something I would expect from a homebrew but not a commercial beer. Pours hazy golden with a huge white lasting head. The most notable part of the aroma is the yeasty esters. Underlying these are hops and some malt. Flavor is interesting. Starts off sweet but then turns dry due to the high level of carbonation. Very noticeable bitterness. Very high carbonation levels, It is ridiculous how much carbonation there is after it warms up. Unique and interesting but loses points due to the absurd level of carbonation.

Pours opaque black. No light comes through whatsoever, not even around the edges of the glass. Head is brown, one of the darker heads Ive seen. Aroma is heavily roasted malt, I dont pick up anything burnt in the aroma. Smells very smooth. Flavor is very dry. Lots of roasted malt, no astringency. Body is surprisingly light considering how rich this beer is. Very nice stout.

Pours white with a dissipating head. Aromas of sweet malt and earthy hops. Flavor is very sweet, actually a bit cloying. Once you get past the sweetness there is a big complex malt flavor with some earthy hops to balance. Not bad. Need some real heavy food to stand up to this beer... good thing Im just about to pull some spares out of the smoker.
Pours very hazy orange with a gigantic head. Highly carbonated. Light yeasty aroma of fruit and spice. Flavor is sweet but balanced by the high carbonation. Very drinkable.
I didnt really get this beer. Just had a very dry earthy aroma. Flavor was dry and earthy as well. Both were very mild. Just wasnt a whole lot there, was looking for more.

Pours light golden with big white lasting head. Aroma is sweet and of malt with a very mild smokiness. Flavor is malty with a more pronounced smoke flavor. Starts of medium-bodied and sweet but finishes dry. Surprisingly refreshing for a smoked beer.

Pours cloudy orange with a small but lasting head. Aroma is of tangerines.   I pick up a certain sour vinegar note everyone once in a while. Not overwhelming but not pleasant. Flavor is very mild, slight caramel flavor but really not much of anything. Light sweetness. Body is medium and creamy. Surprisingly light and drinkable for a 7.5% brew.

This beer is just weird. Pours golden with a slight copper hue. Zero head although there is a fair amount of carbonation. Aroma is sweet with aromas of fermented honey (mead). Flavor is unique. Not sure if I pick up the saffron. This is just a completely new tasting experience and I dont recognize most of the flavors. Ill have to try this one again.
beer_name: Dogfish Head Midas Touch Golden Elixir

review_blob: Pours hazy golden with thin head. Aroma is light and grassy. Just a hint of citrus. Flavor is mildly sweet. Body is light/medium. Im surprised at how mild this beer is overall.

Pours a cloudy pale yellow with big white lasting head. Aroma is quite hoppy, floral. Flavor is unexpectedly harsh, I didnt realize there was rye and wheat in this beer. Grains give a sort of grittiness to the beer. Light and refreshing.

Aroma is barnyard barnyard barnyard. Flavor is sour and refreshing. Its always fun to try sour ales since they are a rare find here in the states. This is the first time Ive sampled one on tap. Refreshing!!!
Smoked malt aroma with some roasted malt to back it. Flavor is roasted/smoked bacon- nice. Body is medium.
Solid IPA here. Potent cascade hops in the aroma. Medium sweetness. Medium body. Long intense bitterness. Very nice.

Pours amber with small head. Aroma is pretty hoppy and seems more American, I was expecting more malt from an ESB. No caramel malt either. Smooth bitterness to finish. Not bad but seems a bit out of style.
Light lager with delicate malty aroma. Hops dont really come through. Some toasted malt. Light body. Drinkable.
